ve a process to end their own lives? Recent research suggests that apoptosis, a form of programmed cell death, first arose billions of years ago in bacteria with a primitive sociality.</div><div class="post__title__actions h5 mt025 flex-auto flex flex-items-center"><div class="comments-button mr05 flex flex-items-center theme__accent"><a href="#comments" class="flex flex-items-center pangram"><svg viewBox="0 0 50 50" enable-background="new 0 0 50 50"><title>Comment</title><path fill="currentColor" d="M9.4 4.2h31.2c8.6 0 9.4 7 9.4 15.6s-.7 15.6-9.4 15.6h-2.2l-.9 9.4-18.8-9.4H9.4c-8.6 0-9.4-7-9.4-15.6S.7 4.2 9.4 4.2z"></path></svg><div><span class="comments-button__count ml075 small mbold disqus-comment-count" data-disqus-identifier="136017 https://www.quantamagazine.org/?p=136017"></span></div></a></div><span class="o-divider mh075 relative"></span><div class="relative"><button class="bookmark-button mh05 flex flex-items-center theme__accent-hover" aria-expanded="false"><svg class="icon" viewBox="0 0 50 50" enable-background="new 0 0 50 50"><title>Save Article</title><path fill="currentColor" d="M2.1 0h45.8v50L25.5 37.5 2.1 50V0z"></path></svg></button><div class="q-tooltip hidden force-mobile-placement" style="width:130px;top:55px;margin-left:-65px"><div class="q-tooltip-content"><div class="q-tooltip-arrow"></div><div class="q-tooltip-inner" role="tooltip"><div class="h6t relative z1 uppercase kern--w mx025"><span class="small no-wrap">Read Later</span></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></section></section></div><figure class="lh-0 w-100P m-0_auto d-flex align-items-center justify-content-center flex-direction-column max-width-1420 _p_last-of-type-mb-0 p-0 _19nesb1 _jrggmc _552kiq _14u1jsz"><div class="w-100P d-flex justify-content-center _149bqoo _q51w3l _10w8956 _1riapq9 image--module"><div class="w-auto max-width-100P max-height-100P mr-0p5em _last-of-type-m-0 _1sv5t9x _1q1eaf2 _pgs2sw _10w8956 component-img"><img alt="An illustration shows a dead cell bursting with a kaleidoscopic outpouring of colors, representing the creative self-destruction of apoptosis." src="https://d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net/uploads/2024/03/CellDeath-byAllisonLi-Lede-scaled.webp" class="w-100P max-width-100P mb-1p5rem _194ln6i _14u1jsz _1sv5t9x border-none"/></div></div><figcaption class="d-block m-0_auto w-100P _ewzkgt _192y3bk _dc69mj"><section class="p-0_3rem _16cxvkm _14u1jsz"><div class="max-width-560px w-100P m-0_auto d-flex flex-direction-column _1e0lyfy _k6y9ug _1ij7gf7 _1xqp4r2 _n5xvur _eugonq _l378w0 _149bqoo _14kcyqx _amwzaw _1re1wwt _pattribution-w-auto _46bwqc _pujp80 _pcaption-w-auto _1dxfdx3"><div class="caption wysiwyg h5 theme__anchors--solid fill-h"><p>Apoptosis is inherently self-destructive, and yet it’s an essential and productive process in complex organisms. Recent research traces its genetic origins to single-celled bacteria.</p>
</div><div class="attribution theme__anchors--solid wysiwyg pangram h6 mb1 fill-h"><p data-pm-slice="1 1 []">Allison Li for <em>Quanta Magazine</em></p>
</div></div></section></figcaption></figure><div class="acf-content scale1 mt2"><div class="post__wrapper scale0 show-dropcap"><div class="mha container--m"><div class="post__content relative flex flex-items-start flex-justify-between"><aside class="post__sidebar hide flex flex-justify-center"><div class="post__sidebar__content"><div class="post__sidebar__content__inner"><div class="align-c mb075"><div class="sidebar__author"><a class="theme__accent-hover transition--color" href="/authors/veronique-greenwood/"><div class="sidebar__author__avatar mha mb1"><div class="image mx0 relative image--circle"><div class="image__inner absolute fit-x"><img class="absolute fit-x fill-h fill-v mxa" alt=""/></div><noscript><img class="absolute fit-x fill-h fill-v is-loaded" src="https://d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net/uploads/2017/04/Greenwood_Nikki.jpg" alt=""/></noscript></div></div><div class="h3t mv05"><span class="screen-reader-text">By </span>Veronique Greenwood</div><p class="h5 o8 mt05 mb1 theme__text"><em>Contributing Writer</em></p></a></div><hr class="mb075 o1"/><p class="h6 o6 mv1 pv025"><em>March 6, 2024</em></p></div><div class="sidebar__actions"><hr class="mt075 mb1 o1"/><a href="#" id="print-friendly-button" class="h6 pangram uppercase mv05 pb1 bold kern flex flex-items-center flex-justify-between sidebar__print transition--color theme__accent-hover"><small>View PDF/Print Mode</small><svg class="icon-l theme__accent ml05" viewBox="0 0 50 50" enable-background="new 0 0 50 50"><path fill="currentColor" d="M39.9,27.5h4.9v22.4H0.1V5.1h22.4V10H5v35h35V27.5z M49.8,0.1h-2.4h-1H33.8V5h7.6L20.7,25.8l3.4,3.4L45,8.4v7.7h4.9V2.6L49.8,0.1z"></path></svg></a></div><div class="mt1 pt05 sidebar__tag-wrap"><a class="sidebar__tag h6 pangram medium inline-block mb0 relative" href="/tag/bacteria/"><span class="absolute fit-x theme__text-background o1"></span><span class="theme__text theme__accent-hover transition--color relative">bacteria</span></a><a class="sidebar__tag h6 pangram medium inline-block mb0 relative" href="/tag/biology/"><span class="absolute fit-x theme__text-background o1"></span><span class="theme__text theme__accent-hover transition--color relative">biology</span></a><a class="sidebar__tag h6 pangram medium inline-block mb0 relative" href="/tag/cell-biology/"><span class="absolute fit-x theme__text-background o1"></span><span class="theme__text theme__accent-hover transition--color relative">cell biology</span></a><a class="sidebar__tag h6 pangram medium inline-block mb0 relative" href="/tag/cells/"><span class="absolute fit-x theme__text-background o1"></span><span class="theme__text theme__accent-hover transition--color relative">cells</span></a><a class="sidebar__tag h6 pangram medium inline-block mb0 relative" href="/tag/eukaryotes/"><span class="absolute fit-x theme__text-background o1"></span><span class="theme__text theme__accent-hover transition--color relative">eukaryotes</span></a><a class="sidebar__tag h6 pangram medium inline-block mb0 relative" href="/tag/evolution/"><span class="absolute fit-x theme__text-background o1"></span><span class="theme__text theme__accent-hover transition--color relative">evolution</span></a><a class="sidebar__tag h6 pangram medium inline-block mb0 relative" href="/tag/mitochondria/"><span class="absolute fit-x theme__text-background o1"></span><span class="theme__text theme__accent-hover transition--color relative">mitochondria</span></a><a class="sidebar__tag h6 pangram medium inline-block mb0 relative" href="/tag/multicellularity/"><span class="absolute fit-x theme__text-background o1"></span><span class="theme__text theme__accent-hover transition--color relative">multicellularity</span></a><a class="sidebar__tag h6 pangram medium inline-block mb0 relative" href="/tag/proteins/"><span class="absolute fit-x theme__text-background o1"></span><span class="theme__text theme__accent-hover transition--color relative">proteins</span></a><a class="sidebar__tag h6 pangram medium inline-block mb0 relative theme__accent" href="/topics"><span class="absolute fit-x theme__text-background o1"></span><span class="theme__text-hover transition--color relative">All topics</span><svg class="ml05 icon" viewBox="0 0 50 50" enable-background="new 0 0 50 50"><path fill="currentColor" d="M50 25l-17.4-8.7v6.5H0v4.4h32.6v6.5"></path></svg></a></div></div><div class="sidebar__poster"><a href="https://www.quantamagazine.org/joy" title="The Joy of Why with Steven Strogatz and Janna Levin. New episodes every other Thursday." class="sidebar__poster__desktop" target="_blank"><img src="https://d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net/uploads/2024/01/JoY-Ads-2024_Article.jpg" alt="The Joy of Why with Steven Strogatz and Janna Levin. New episodes every other Thursday." class="fill-h"/></a><a href="https://www.quantamagazine.org/joy" title="The Joy of Why with Steven Strogatz and Janna Levin. New episodes every other Thursday." class="sidebar__poster__mobile" target="_blank"><img src="https://d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net/uploads/2024/01/JoY-Ads-2024_Mobile.webp" alt="The Joy of Why with Steven Strogatz and Janna Levin. New episodes every other Thursday." class="fill-h"/></a></div></div></aside><section class="outer mha js-router-anchors outer--content"><div class="flex-auto mha container--xs"><div class="post__content__section wysiwyg p theme__anchors--underline"><h2 class="screen-reader-text">Introduction</h2><div class="post__content wysiwyg p theme__anchors--underline"><p>It can be hard to tell, at first, when a cell is on the verge of self-destruction.</p>
<p>It appears to be going about its usual business, transcribing genes and making proteins. The powerhouse organelles called mitochondria are dutifully churning out energy. But then a mitochondrion receives a signal, and its typically placid proteins join forces to form a death machine.</p>
<p>They slice through the cell with breathtaking thoroughness. In a matter of hours, all that the cell had built lies in ruins. A few bubbles of membrane are all that remains.</p>
<p>“It’s really amazing how fast, how organized it is,” said <a href="https://vip.ext.unb.ca/amnedelcu/">Aurora Nedelcu</a>, an evolutionary biologist at the University of New Brunswick who has studied the process in algae.</p>
<p>Apoptosis, as this process is known, seems as unlikely as it is violent. And yet some cells undergo this devastating but predictable series of steps to kill themselves on purpose. When biologists first observed it, they were shocked to find self-induced death among living, striving organisms. And although it turned out that apoptosis is a vital creative force for many multicellular creatures, to a given cell it is utterly ruinous. How could a behavior that results in a cell’s sudden death evolve, let alone persist?</p>
<p>The tools for apoptosis, molecular biologists have found, are curiously widespread. And as they have sought to understand its molecular process and origins, they’ve found something even more surprising: Apoptosis can be traced back to ancient forms of programmed cell death undertaken by single-celled organisms — even bacteria — that seem to have evolved it as a social behavior.</p>
</div></div></div></section><aside class="post__sidebar hide flex flex-justify-center theme__anchors--solid"><div class="post__sidebar__content"><div class="post__sidebar__content__inner"><div class="h3t mt0">Share this article</div><div><div class="social-links social-links--share flex flex-justify-between"><a href="http://www.facebook.com/sharer.php?u=https://www.quantamagazine.org/cellular-self-destruction-may-be-ancient-but-why-20240306/" target="_blank" class="social-links__link flex flex-items-center relative facebook"><div class="icon-button inline-block relative pointer _hover_div-c-ff8600 _hover_div-opacity-1 _hover_svg-c-ff8600"><div class="absolute fit-x mxa o2 c-1a1a1a"></div><svg class="absolute fit-x mxa c-1a1a1a" viewBox="0 0 50 50" enable-background="new 0 0 50 50"><title>Facebook</title><path fill="currentColor" d="M13 16.5h5.1v-5c-.2-2.7.3-5.4 1.7-7.7 1.8-2.5 4.9-4 8-3.8 3.1-.1 6.2.2 9.2 1l-1.3 7.7C34.4 8.3 33 8 31.6 8c-2 0-3.8.7-3.8 2.7v5.9H36l-.6 7.5h-7.6V50h-9.6V23.9H13v-7.4z"></path></svg></div></a><a href="https://twitter.com/share?url=https://www.quantamagazine.org/cellular-self-destruction-may-be-ancient-but-why-20240306/&amp;text=Cellular%20Self-Destruction%20May%20Be%20Ancient.%20But%20Why?&amp;via=QuantaMagazine" target="_blank" class="social-links__link flex flex-items-center relative twitter"><div class="icon-button inline-block relative pointer _hover_div-c-ff8600 _hover_div-opacity-1 _hover_svg-c-ff8600"><div class="absolute fit-x mxa o2 c-1a1a1a"></div><svg class="absolute fit-x mxa c-1a1a1a" viewBox="0 0 50 50" enable-background="new 0 0 50 50"><title>Twitter</title><path fill="currentColor" d="M50 9.9c-1.9.8-3.8 1.3-5.9 1.6 2.1-1.3 3.7-3.2 4.5-5.6-2 1.2-4.2 2-6.5 2.5-3.8-4.1-10.3-4.5-14.5-.8-2.8 2.5-4 6.3-3.1 10-8.2-.5-15.8-4.3-21-10.6-2.7 4.6-1.3 10.5 3.2 13.5C5 20.4 3.4 20 2 19.2c0 4.8 3.4 8.9 8.2 9.9-.9.2-1.8.4-2.7.3-.6 0-1.3-.1-1.9-.2 1.3 4.1 5.2 6.9 9.5 7C10.8 39.5 5.4 41 0 40.4c13.5 8.5 31.5 4.6 40.2-8.7 3-4.6 4.6-10 4.6-15.5