zes"},"__typename":"Image"},"$Post:136017.acf.modules.4.sets.0.mobile_zoom_image.sizes":{"thumbnail":null,"square_small":null,"square_large":null,"medium":null,"medium_large":null,"large":null,"__typename":"ImageSizes"},"$Post:136017.acf.modules.5":{"hide_this_component":null,"acf_fc_layout":"content_area","show_sidebars":false,"content":"\u003cp>Experts assumed, though, that this skill was unique to multicellular organisms, which had bodies made of many cells for which other cells could die. What possible good could a single-celled organism reap from its own death? Evolution could hardly favor a behavior that removed its carrier from the gene pool.\u003c/p>\n\u003cp>“It didn’t seem to make sense why anything would actively kill itself,” said \u003ca href=\"https://stias.ac.za/fellows/pierre-durand/\">Pierre Durand\u003c/a>, an evolutionary biologist at the University of the Witwatersrand in South Africa.\u003c/p>\n\u003cp>But as scientists sketched these death protocols in greater detail, some began to realize that single-celled eukaryotes had similar tools and abilities. In 1997, a team of researchers led by the biochemist \u003ca href=\"https://phos4us.at/kai-uwe-frohlich/\">Kai-Uwe Fröhlich\u003c/a> reported yeast cells \u003ca href=\"https://doi.org/10.1083/jcb.139.3.729\">methodically dismantling themselves\u003c/a> — the first known instance of a “unicellular lower eukaryote” having the basic machinery of programmed cell death. Soon, single-celled algae, protists and other fungi joined the ranks of creatures known for self-induced death.\u003c/p>\n\u003cp>As biologists tried to understand how organisms could have evolved this ability, they were forced to grapple with another question: If programmed cell death didn’t appear with multicellularity, then where did it come from?\u003c/p>\n\u003ch2>\u003cstrong>The Tools for the Job\u003c/strong>\u003c/h2>\n\u003cp>Here is what happens when a eukaryotic cell dooms itself to die.\u003c/p>\n\u003cp>First, there comes a signal that the end has come. If it’s from outside the cell — if the surrounding cells have marked their neighbor for death — the signal arrives at the cell’s surface and binds a death receptor, which jump-starts apoptosis. If the signal comes from inside the cell — if the reason for death is damage to the genome, for instance — then the process starts with the mitochondria turning against their host cell.\u003c/p>\n\u003cp>In either case, specialized enzymes soon leap into action. Some apoptotic factors, such as caspases in animals, can activate each other in a cascade of startling swiftness that becomes a swarm and cuts the cell’s structures to ribbons. After that, the cell’s fate is sealed.\u003c/p>\n\u003cp>“There are many roads to cell death,” said \u003ca href=\"https://irp.nih.gov/pi/aravind-iyer\">L. Aravind,\u003c/a> an evolutionary biologist at the National Center for Biotechnology Information. They all end with apoptotic enzymes, and with fragments of protein and DNA where a cell used to be.\u003c/p>\n\u003cp>Apoptosis is so tightly controlled, and so widely practiced, that it’s hard not to wonder where its mechanisms originated — both the pieces that make up the machine, which must have come first, and the ways they work together. That curiosity is what drove Szymon Kaczanowski and \u003ca href=\"https://ibb.edu.pl/en/laboratory/urszula-zielenkiewicz/\">Urszula Zielenkiewicz\u003c/a> of the Polish Academy of Sciences to a recent set of experiments. They wanted to know whether apoptotic proteins from one eukaryote would function if plugged into the apoptotic machine of a distant relative. If the process still worked, they figured, then the enzymes’ functions — the way they slice and dice DNA or activate other parts of the machinery — must have been largely conserved over long periods of time.\u003c/p>\n","fadein":false,"__typename":"ACFContent"},"$Post:136017.acf.modules.6":{"hide_this_component":null,"acf_fc_layout":"image_component","layout":"inline","regular_caption_right":true,"settings":"","attribution":"\u003cp>Courtesy of Urszula Zielenkiewicz and Szymon Kaczanowski\u003c/p>\n","caption":"\u003cp>Urszula Zielenkiewicz and Szymon Kaczanowski recently found that apoptotic proteins from across the eukaryotic tree of life work when plugged into yeast cells — suggesting that the process originated with their common ancestor.\u003c/p>\n","mobile_comp_caption":"","mobile_comp_attribution":"","sets":[{"type":"id","generated":true,"id":"$Post:136017.acf.modules.6.sets.0","typename":"ImageSet"}],"__typename":"ACFImageComponent"},"$Post:136017.acf.modules.6.sets.0":{"settings":"","image":{"type":"id","generated":true,"id":"$Post:136017.acf.modules.6.sets.0.image","typename":"Image"},"mobile_image":{"type":"id","generated":true,"id":"$Post:136017.acf.modules.6.sets.0.mobile_image","typename":"Image"},"mobile_side_margins":false,"mobile_width_constraint":"","mobile_caption":"","mobile_attribution":"","zoom_image":{"type":"id","generated":true,"id":"$Post:136017.acf.modules.6.sets.0.zoom_image","typename":"Image"},"zoom_caption":"","zoom_attribution":"","mobile_zoom_image":{"type":"id","generated":true,"id":"$Post:136017.acf.modules.6.sets.0.mobile_zoom_image","typename":"Image"},"mobile_zoom_caption":"","mobile_zoom_attribution":"","external_link":"","__typename":"ImageSet"},"$Post:136017.acf.modules.6.sets.0.image":{"alt":"Urszula Zielenkiewicz and Szymon Kaczanowski point to a scientific poster describing their apoptosis research.","caption":"","url":"https://d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net/uploads/2024/03/UrszulaZielenkiewicz_and_SzymonKaczanowski-courtestyofUrszulaZielenkiewicz_and_SzymonKaczanowski.webp","width":1600,"height":2178,"sizes":{"type":"id","generated":true,"id":"$Post:136017.acf.modules.6.sets.0.image.sizes","typename":"ImageSizes"},"__typename":"Image"},"$Post:136017.acf.modules.6.sets.0.image.sizes":{"thumbnail":"https://d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net/uploads/2024/03/UrszulaZielenkiewicz_and_SzymonKaczanowski-courtestyofUrszulaZielenkiewicz_and_SzymonKaczanowski-382x520.webp","square_small":"https://d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net/uploads/2024/03/UrszulaZielenkiewicz_and_SzymonKaczanowski-courtestyofUrszulaZielenkiewicz_and_SzymonKaczanowski-160x160.webp","square_large":"https://d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net/uploads/2024/03/UrszulaZielenkiewicz_and_SzymonKaczanowski-courtestyofUrszulaZielenkiewicz_and_SzymonKaczanowski-520x520.webp","medium":"https://d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net/uploads/2024/03/UrszulaZielenkiewicz_and_SzymonKaczanowski-courtestyofUrszulaZielenkiewicz_and_SzymonKaczanowski-1264x1720.webp","medium_large":"https://d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net/uploads/2024/03/UrszulaZielenkiewicz_and_SzymonKaczanowski-courtestyofUrszulaZielenkiewicz_and_SzymonKaczanowski-768x1045.webp","large":"https://d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net/uploads/2024/03/UrszulaZielenkiewicz_and_SzymonKaczanowski-courtestyofUrszulaZielenkiewicz_and_SzymonKaczanowski.webp","__typename":"ImageSizes"},"$Post:136017.acf.modules.6.sets.0.mobile_image":{"alt":null,"caption":null,"url":null,"width":null,"height":null,"sizes":{"type":"id","generated":true,"id":"$Post:136017.acf.modules.6.sets.0.mobile_image.sizes","typename":"ImageSizes"},"__typename":"Image"},"$Post:136017.acf.modules.6.sets.0.mobile_image.sizes":{"thumbnail":null,"square_small":null,"square_large":null,"medium":null,"medium_large":null,"large":null,"__typename":"ImageSizes"},"$Post:136017.acf.modules.6.sets.0.zoom_image":{"alt":null,"caption":null,"url":null,"width":null,"height":null,"sizes":{"type":"id","generated":true,"id":"$Post:136017.acf.modules.6.sets.0.zoom_image.sizes","typename":"ImageSizes"},"__typename":"Image"},"$Post:136017.acf.modules.6.sets.0.zoom_image.sizes":{"thumbnail":null,"square_small":null,"square_large":null,"medium":null,"medium_large":null,"large":null,"__typename":"ImageSizes"},"$Post:136017.acf.modules.6.sets.0.mobile_zoom_image":{"alt":null,"caption":null,"url":null,"width":null,"height":null,"sizes":{"type":"id","generated":true,"id":"$Post:136017.acf.modules.6.sets.0.mobile_zoom_image.sizes","typename":"ImageSizes"},"__typename":"Image"},"$Post:136017.acf.modules.6.sets.0.mobile_zoom_image.sizes":{"thumbnail":null,"square_small":null,"square_large":null,"medium":null,"medium_large":null,"large":null,"__typename":"ImageSizes"},"$Post:136017.acf.modules.7":{"hide_this_component":null,"acf_fc_layout":"content_area","show_sidebars":false,"content":"\u003cp>The team engineered yeast chimeras that had apoptotic enzymes from across the eukaryotic world: from mustard plants, slime molds, humans and the parasite that causes leishmaniasis. Then, the researchers induced apoptosis. They saw that many of these chimeras were able to execute themselves regardless of the proteins’ origins. What’s more, “the different hallmarks of apoptosis are frequently maintained,” Kaczanowski said, including DNA breakage and condensation of chromatin in the nucleus.\u003c/p>\n\u003cp>They wondered, too, whether bacterial proteins could stand in for eukaryotic ones. When they subbed in analogue protein genes from a handful of bacteria, the team observed programmed death in some chimeras, but not all. That suggested that the tools for self-induced death predated even the eukaryotes, the researchers concluded.\u003c/p>\n\u003cdiv id='component-65f214311109d' class=''>\u003cscript type=\"text/template\">{\"type\":\"Blockquote\",\"id\":\"component-65f214311109d\",\"data\":{\"quote\":\"\u003cp>Maybe, once caught inside our ancient ancestor, apoptotic proteins became a way for the mitochondrion to stress the host into changing its behavior.\u003c\\/p>\\n\",\"alignment\":\"right\",\"quote_attribution\":\"\",\"twitter_text\":\"\"}}\u003c\/script>\u003c/div>\n\u003cp>Not everyone agrees with their interpretation. Some of these proteins, especially those that cut DNA and proteins, are dangerous for the cell, Aravind said; a cell might die simply because of the damage, rather than because of an apoptotic process.\u003c/p>\n\u003cp>Still, Kaczanowski and Zielenkiewicz believe that what they are seeing is true programmed cell death. And one of their speculations about why bacterial genes might work in eukaryotes connects with an idea that’s been bandied about by biologists for decades.\u003c/p>\n\u003cp>The theory involves the mitochondrion — an organelle that was once a free-living bacterium. It is the cell’s energy producer. It also crops up again and again in apoptosis pathways. Guido Kroemer, who studies the role of mitochondria in apoptosis, dubbed them “\u003ca href=\"https://doi.org/10.1002/1521-1878(200102)23:2%3c111::AID-BIES1016%3e3.0.CO;2-Y\">the suicide organelles\u003c/a>.”\u003c/p>\n\u003cp>“Many call it,” Nedelcu said, “the central executioner of cell death.”\u003c/p>\n\u003ch2>\u003cstrong>An Inside Job?\u003c/strong>\u003c/h2>\n\u003cp>The mitochondrion is a pretty little thing under the microscope, a neat lozenge containing a labyrinth of membranes. It breaks sugars down to generate ATP, a molecule whose energy powers nearly every cellular process. We don’t know precisely how it wound up within us: The original bacterium might have been the prey of our single-celled ancestor and then escaped digestion by means still mysterious. It might have been a neighbor cell, sharing resources with our ancestor until their fates were so intertwined that their bodies became one.\u003c/p>\n\u003cp>Whatever its origins, the mitochondrion has its own small genome, left over from its days of independence. But many of its genes have moved to the host’s genome. In 2002, Aravind and Eugene Koonin wrote \u003ca href=\"https://doi.org/10.1038/sj.cdd.4400991\">a landmark paper\u003c/a> considering the idea that eukaryotes may have gotten some of their apoptosis genes from the mitochondrion. This little remnant of a bacterium might be the source of some tools eukaryotic cells use to kill themselves.\u003c/p>\n","fadein":false,"__typename":"ACFContent"},"$Post:136017.acf.modules.8":{"hide_this_component":null,"acf_fc_layout":"image_component","layout":"regular","regular_caption_right":false,"settings":"","attribution":"\u003cp>Steve Gschmeissner/Science Source\u003c/p>\n","caption":"\u003cp>A kidney cell in the early stages of apoptosis shows its hallmark “blebbing” on a colored scanning electron micrograph. Its membrane bubbles and deforms as the cell dismantles its internal structures.\u003c/p>\n","mobile_comp_caption":"","mobile_comp_attribution":"","sets":[{"type":"id","generated":true,"id":"$Post:136017.acf.modules.8.sets.0","typename":"ImageSet"}],"__typename":"ACFImageComponent"},"$Post:136017.acf.modules.8.sets.0":{"settings":"","image":{"type":"id","generated":true,"id":"$Post:136017.acf.modules.8.sets.0.image","typename":"Image"},"mobile_image":{"type":"id","generated":true,"id":"$Post:136017.acf.modules.8.sets.0.mobile_image","typename":"Image"},"mobile_side_margins":false,"mobile_width_constraint":"","mobile_caption":"","mobile_attribution":"","zoom_image":{"type":"id","generated":true,"id":"$Post:136017.acf.modules.8.sets.0.zoom_image","typename":"Image"},"zoom_caption":"","zoom_attribution":"","mobile_zoom_image":{"type":"id","generated":true,"id":"$Post:136017.acf.modules.8.sets.0.mobile_zoom_image","typename":"Image"},"mobile_zoom_caption":"","mobile_zoom_attribution":"","external_link":"","__typename":"ImageSet"},"$Post:136017.acf.modules.8.sets.0.image":{"alt":"A red-colored cell membrane forms elongated bubbles, a sign of apoptosis.","caption":"","url":"https://d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net/uploads/2024/03/CellApoptosis-BY-SteveGschmeissner_ScienceSource-scaled.webp","width":2560,"height":2449,"sizes":{"type":"id","generated":true,"id":"$Post:136017.acf.modules.8.sets.0.image.sizes","typename":"ImageSizes"},"__typename":"Image"},"$Post:136017.acf.modules.8.sets.0.image.sizes":{"thumbnail":"https://d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net/uploads/2024/03/CellApoptosis-BY-SteveGschmeissner_ScienceSource-520x497.webp","square_small":"https://d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net/uploads/2024/03/CellApoptosis-BY-SteveGschmeissner_ScienceSource-160x160.webp","square_large":"https://d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net/uploads/2024/03/CellApoptosis-BY-SteveGschmeissner_ScienceSource-520x520.webp","medium":"https://d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net/uploads/2024/03/CellApoptosis-BY-SteveGschmeissner_ScienceSource-1720x1645.webp","medium_large":"https://d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net/uploads/2024/03/CellApoptosis-BY-SteveGschmeissner_ScienceSource-768x735.webp","large":"https://d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net/uploads/2024/03/CellApoptosis-BY-SteveGschmeissner_ScienceSource-scaled.webp","__typename":"ImageSizes"},"$Post:136017.acf.modules.8.sets.0.mobile_image":{"alt":null,"caption":null,"url":null,"width":null,"height":null,"sizes":{"type":"id","generated":true,"id":"$Post:136017.acf.modules.8.sets.0.mobile_image.sizes","typename":"ImageSizes"},"__typename":"Image"},"$Post:136017.acf.modules.8.sets.0.mobile_image.sizes":{"thumbnail":null,"square_small":null,"square_large":null,"medium":null,"medium_large":null,"large":null,"__typename":"ImageSizes"},"$Post:136017.acf.modules.8.sets.0.zoom_image":{"alt":null,"caption":null,"url":null,"width":null,"height":null,"sizes":{"type":"id","generated":true,"id":"$Post:136017.acf.modules.8.sets.0.zoom_image.sizes","typename":"ImageSizes"},"__typename":"Image"},"$Post:136017.acf.modules.8.sets.0.zoom_image.sizes":{"thumbnail":null,"square_small":null,"square_large":null,"medium":null,"medium_large":null,"large":null,"__typename":"ImageSizes"},"$Post:136017.acf.modules.8.sets.0.mobile_zoom_image":{"alt":null,"caption":null,"url":null,"width":null,"height":null,"sizes":{"type":"id","generated":true,"id":"$Post:136017.acf.modules.8.sets.0.mobile_zoom_image.sizes","typename":"ImageSizes"},"__typename":"Image"},"$Post:136017.acf.modules.8.sets.0.mobile_zoom_image.sizes":{"thumbnail":null,"square_small":null,"square_large":null,"medium":null,"medium_large":null,"large":null,"__typename":"ImageSizes"},"$Post:136017.acf.modules.9":{"hide_this_component":null,"acf_fc_layout":"content_area","show_sidebars":false,"content":"\u003cp>The genes for apoptosis reminded Kaczanowski and Zielenkiewicz of an arms race between a predator and its prey. In their new paper, they speculated that they might be holdovers from the tools evolved by a prey organism, presumably the original mitochondrial bacterium, to defend itself.\u003c/p>\n\u003cp>Maybe, once caught inside our ancient ancestor, apoptotic proteins became a way for the mitochondrion to stress the host into changing its behavior, goes a hypothesis collected by Durand and Grant Ramsey, a philosopher of science, \u003ca href=\"https://doi.org/10.1007/s40656-023-00581-8\">in a review\u003c/a> they published last June. Or maybe they are the remnants of a way the mitochondrion ensured that the host could not get rid of it — a poison for which only the mitochondria possessed the antidote. Somewhere along the way, the process was captured or transformed by the host, and a variant evolved into apoptosis proper.\u003c/p>\n\u003cp>The search for answers about the origin of eukaryotic apoptosis seems to be drawing researchers deeper into the bacterial world. In fact, \u003ca href=\"https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.ppat.1010879\">some wonder\u003c/a> whether the answers may lie in why single-celled organisms take their own lives. If some form of programmed cell death is older than multicellular life — older even than eukaryotes — then perhaps understanding why it happens in organisms with no bodies to benefit and no mitochondria to speed the process can explain how this all got started.\u003c/p>\n\u003ch2>\u003cstrong>For the Good of Some Whole\u003c/strong>\u003c/h2>\n\u003cp>Here’s one reason a single-celled organism might choose to die: to help its neighbors.\u003c/p>\n\u003cp>In the 2000s, when Durand was a postdoctoral researcher at the University of Arizona, he discovered something intriguing during \u003ca href=\"https://doi.org/10.1086/657686\">an experiment with single-celled eukaryotic algae\u003c/a>. When he fed algae the remains of their kin who had died by programmed cell death, the living cells flourished. But when he fed them the remains of kin killed violently, the algae’s growth slowed.\u003c/p>\n\u003cdiv id='component-65f2143113b2b' class=''>\u003cscript type=\"text/template\">{\"type\":\"Image\",\"id\":\"component-65f2143113b2b\",\"data\":{\"id\":136032,\"src\":\"https:\\/\\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\\/uploads\\/2024\\/03\\/PierreMDurand-courtesyofStellenboschInsituteforAdvancedStudy.webp\",\"alt\":\"Portrait of Pierre Durand\",\"class\":\"\",\"width\":814,\"height\":782,\"mobileSrc\":false,\"zoomSrc\":false,\"mobileZoomSrc\":false,\"align\":\"align=\\\"right\\\"\",\"wrapper_width\":\"\",\"caption\":\"\u003cp>Over a decade ago, Pierre Durand discovered that an alga\\u2019s programmed cell death can provide nutrition to its relatives. He\\u2019s spent much of his career pondering the mystery of how self-induced death could evolve.\u003c\\/p>\\n\",\"attribution\":\"\u003cp>Courtesy of Stellenbosch Insitute for Advanced Study\u003c\\/p>\\n\",\"variant\":\"shortcode\",\"size\":\"default\",\"disableZoom\":true,\"disableMobileZoom\":false,\"srcImage\":{\"ID\":136032,\"id\":136032,\"title\":\"PierreMDurand-courtesyofStellenboschInsituteforAdvancedStudy\",\"filename\":\"PierreMDurand-courtesyofStellenboschInsituteforAdvancedStudy.webp\",\"filesize\":49724,\"url\":\"https:\\/\\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\\/uploads\\/2024\\/03\\/PierreMDurand-courtesyofStellenboschInsituteforAdvancedStudy.webp\",\"link\":\"https:\\/\\/www.quantamagazine.org\\/cellular-self-destruction-may-be-ancient-but-why-20240306\\/pierremdurand-courtesyofstellenboschinsituteforadvancedstudy\\/\",\"alt\":\"Portrait of Pierre Durand\",\"author\":\"45758\",\"description\":\"\",\"caption\":\"\",\"name\":\"pierremdurand-courtesyofstellenboschinsituteforadvancedstudy\",\"status\":\"inherit\",\"uploaded_to\":136017,\"date\":\"2024-03-05 18:34:28\",\"modified\":\"2024-03-05 18:37:47\",\"menu_order\":0,\"mime_type\":\"image\\/webp\",\"type\":\"image\",\"subtype\":\"webp\",\"icon\":\"https:\\/\\/api.quantamagazine.org\\/wp-includes\\/images\\/media\\/default.png\",\"width\":814,\"height\":782,\"sizes\":{\"thumbnail\":\"https:\\/\\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\\/uploads\\/2024\\/03\\/PierreMDurand-courtesyofStellenboschInsituteforAdvancedStudy-520x500.webp\",\"thumbnail-width\":520,\"thumbnail-height\":500,\"medium\":\"https:\\/\\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\\/uploads\\/2024\\/03\\/PierreMDurand-courtesyofStellenboschInsituteforAdvancedStudy.webp\",\"medium-width\":814,\"medium-height\":782,\"medium_large\":\"https:\\/\\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\\/uploads\\/2024\\/03\\/PierreMDurand-courtesyofStellenboschInsituteforAdvancedStudy-768x738.webp\",\"medium_large-width\":768,\"medium_large-height\":738,\"large\":\"https:\\/\\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\\/uploads\\/2024\\/03\\/PierreMDurand-courtesyofStellenboschInsituteforAdvancedStudy.webp\",\"large-width\":814,\"large-height\":782,\"1536x1536\":\"https:\\/\\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\\/uploads\\/2024\\/03\\/PierreMDurand-courtesyofStellenboschInsituteforAdvancedStudy.webp\",\"1536x1536-width\":814,\"1536x1536-height\":782,\"2048x2048\":\"https:\\/\\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\\/uploads\\/2024\\/03\\/PierreMDurand-courtesyofStellenboschInsituteforAdvancedStudy.webp\",\"2048x2048-width\":814,\"2048x2048-height\":782,\"square_small\":\"https:\\/\\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\\/uploads\\/2024\\/03\\/PierreMDurand-courtesyofStellenboschInsituteforAdvancedStudy-160x160.webp\",\"square_small-width\":160,\"square_small-height\":160,\"square_large\":\"https:\\/\\/d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net\\/uploads\\/2024\\/03\\/PierreMDurand-courtesyofStellenboschInsituteforAdvancedStudy-520x520.webp\",\"square_large-width\":520,\"square_large-height\":520}},\"largeForPrint\":true,\"externalLink\":\"\",\"original_resolution\":false}}\u003c\/script>\u003c/div>\n\u003cp>Programmed cell death appeared to create usable resources from dead parts. However, this process could only benefit relatives of the dead algae, he found. “It was actually harmful to those of a different species,” Durand said. In 2022, another research group \u003ca href=\"https://doi.org/10.1098/rsbl.2022.0259\">confirmed the finding\u003c/a> in another algae.\u003c/p>\n\u003cp>The results possibly explain how cell death can evolve in single-celled creatures. If an organism is surrounded by kin, then its death can provide nutrition and therefore further its relatives’ survival. That creates an opening for natural selection to select for the tools for self-induced death.\u003c/p>\n\u003cp>Bacteria, too, are single-celled, and may live among their kin. Can they also die for some greater good? There are hints that \u003ca href=\"https://doi.org/10.1098/rspb.2012.3035\">under the right conditions\u003c/a>, bacteria infected with a virus may kill themselves to arrest the spread of disease. These revelations have reshaped how researchers think about programmed cell death, and Aravind recently discovered \u003ca href=\"https://doi.org/10.1016/j.cell.2023.04.015\">another piece of the puzzle\u003c/a>.\u003c/p>\n\u003cp>It involves protein regions called \u003ca href=\"https://doi.org/10.1016/S0968-0004(00)01577-2\">NACHT domains\u003c/a>, which appear in some animal apoptosis proteins. NACHT domains also exist in bacteria. In fact, in the wild, the microbes that have the most NACHT domains sometimes partake of what looks very much like multicellular living, Aravind said. They grow in colonies, which makes them especially vulnerable to contagion and especially likely to benefit from each other’s self-sacrifice.\u003c/p>\n\u003cp>Aravind’s colleague \u003ca href=\"https://www.colorado.edu/lab/aaron-whiteley/aaron-whiteley\">Aaron Whiteley\u003c/a> and his lab at University of Colorado and his lab equipped \u003cem>E. coli\u003c/em> with NACHT domains and grew them in test tubes. Then they infected the cells with viruses. Strikingly, they found that NACHT-bearing proteins were required to trigger a form of programmed cell death, with infected cells killing themselves so swiftly that the viruses were unable to replicate. Their sacrifice could protect others around them from infection, Aravind said.\u003c/p>\n","fadein":false,"__typename":"ACFContent"},"$Post:136017.acf.modules.10":{"hide_this_component":null,"acf_fc_layout":"image_component","layout":"regular","regular_caption_right":false,"settings":"","attribution":"\u003cp>Laks Iyer\u003c/p>\n","caption":"\u003cp>More than 20 years ago, L. Aravind (pictured here holding a model of a molecule targeted by programmed cell death) posited that eukaryotes gained tools for apoptosis when they acquired mitochondria. Today he believes they gained apoptotic proteins from other ancient bacteria.\u003c/p>\n","mobile_comp_caption":"","mobile_comp_attribution":"","sets":[{"type":"id","generated":true,"id":"$Post:136017.acf.modules.10.sets.0","typename":"ImageSet"}],"__typename":"ACFImageComponent"},"$Post:136017.acf.modules.10.sets.0":{"settings":"","image":{"type":"id","generated":true,"id":"$Post:136017.acf.modules.10.sets.0.image","typename":"Image"},"mobile_image":{"type":"id","generated":true,"id":"$Post:136017.acf.modules.10.sets.0.mobile_image","typename":"Image"},"mobile_side_margins":false,"mobile_width_constraint":"","mobile_caption":"","mobile_attribution":"","zoom_image":{"type":"id","generated":true,"id":"$Post:136017.acf.modules.10.sets.0.zoom_image","typename":"Image"},"zoom_caption":"","zoom_attribution":"","mobile_zoom_image":{"type":"id","generated":true,"id":"$Post:136017.acf.modules.10.sets.0.mobile_zoom_image","typename":"Image"},"mobile_zoom_caption":"","mobile_zoom_attribution":"","external_link":"","__typename":"ImageSet"},"$Post:136017.acf.modules.10.sets.0.image":{"alt":"L. Aravind holds a plastic molecular model of nicotinamide dinucleotide, which is targeted in several forms of programmed cell death.","caption":"","url":"https://d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net/uploads/2024/03/Aravind-byLaksIyer.webp","width":2400,"height":1463,"sizes":{"type":"id","generated":true,"id":"$Post:136017.acf.modules.10.sets.0.image.sizes","typename":"ImageSizes"},"__typename":"Image"},"$Post:136017.acf.modules.10.sets.0.image.sizes":{"thumbnail":"https://d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net/uploads/2024/03/Aravind-byLaksIyer-520x317.webp","square_small":"https://d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net/uploads/2024/03/Aravind-byLaksIyer-160x160.webp","square_large":"https://d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net/uploads/2024/03/Aravind-byLaksIyer-520x520.webp","medium":"https://d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net/uploads/2024/03/Aravind-byLaksIyer-1720x1048.webp","medium_large":"https://d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net/uploads/2024/03/Aravind-byLaksIyer-768x468.webp","large":"https://d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net/uploads/2024/03/Aravind-byLaksIyer.webp","__typename":"ImageSizes"},"$Post:136017.acf.modules.10.sets.0.mobile_image":{"alt":null,"caption":null,"url":null,"width":null,"height":null,"sizes":{"type":"id","generated":true,"id":"$Post:136017.acf.modules.10.sets.0.mobile_image.sizes","typename":"ImageSizes"},"__typename":"Image"},"$Post:136017.acf.modules.10.sets.0.mobile_image.sizes":{"thumbnail":null,"square_small":null,"square_large":null,"medium":null,"medium_large":null,"large":null,"__typename":"ImageSizes"},"$Post:136017.acf.modules.10.sets.0.zoom_image":{"alt":null,"caption":null,"url":null,"width":null,"height":null,"sizes":{"type":"id","generated":true,"id":"$Post:136017.acf.modules.10.sets.0.zoom_image.sizes","typename":"ImageSizes"},"__typename":"Image"},"$Post:136017.acf.modules.10.sets.0.zoom_image.sizes":{"thumbnail":null,"square_small":null,"square_large":null,"medium":null,"medium_large":null,"large":null,"__typename":"ImageSizes"},"$Post:136017.acf.modules.10.sets.0.mobile_zoom_image":{"alt":null,"caption":null,"url":null,"width":null,"height":null,"sizes":{"type":"id","generated":true,"id":"$Post:136017.acf.modules.10.sets.0.mobile_zoom_image.sizes","typename":"ImageSizes"},"__typename":"Image"},"$Post:136017.acf.modules.10.sets.0.mobile_zoom_image.sizes":{"thumbnail":null,"square_small":null,"square_large":null,"medium":null,"medium_large":null,"large":null,"__typename":"ImageSizes"},"$Post:136017.acf.modules.11":{"hide_this_component":null,"acf_fc_layout":"content_area","show_sidebars":false,"content":"\u003cp>These preserved domains tell a story of apoptotic origins, according to Aravind. “You already had a premade cell-death apparatus that was there in certain bacteria,” he said. Then, at some point, some lineages of eukaryotic cells picked up this toolkit, which eventually endowed cells in multicellular organisms with a way to die for the greater good.\u003c/p>\n\u003cp>He no longer believes the evidence points to the mitochondrion as the only bacterial source of apoptosis proteins. The mitochondrion is the primary bacterial leftover still living within most eukaryotic cells, and 25 years ago it was the logical candidate for these mysterious genes, he said. In the years since, however, something else has become clear: The mitochondrion probably wasn’t alone.\u003c/p>\n\u003ch2>\u003cstrong>The Bacteria in Us\u003c/strong>\u003c/h2>\n\u003cp>Eukaryotic genomes, researchers have gradually realized, bear many traces of bacterial genes, remnants of a silent parade of other creatures that left their marks on us. They may have been symbionts, like the mitochondrion, that \u003ca href=\"https://www.quantamagazine.org/rethinking-the-ancestry-of-the-eukaryotes-20190409/\">popped in and out\u003c/a> of various eukaryotic lineages, leaving genes behind. “We should now realize that this situation probably continued all through eukaryotic evolution,” Aravind said.\u003c/p>\n\u003cdiv id='component-65f21431161d3' class='related-list'>\u003cscript type=\"text/template\">{\"type\":\"LinkList\",\"id\":\"component-65f21431161d3\",\"data\":{\"title\":\"Related:\",\"class\":\"related-list\",\"links\":[{\"type\":\"internal\",\"link\":\"https:\\/\\/www.quantamagazine.org\\/cellular-life-death-and-everything-in-between-20190708\\/\",\"title\":\"Cellular Life, Death and Everything in Between\"},{\"type\":\"internal\",\"link\":\"https:\\/\\/www.quantamagazine.org\\/rethinking-the-ancestry-of-the-eukaryotes-20190409\\/\",\"title\":\"Researchers Rethink the Ancestry of Complex Cells\"},{\"type\":\"internal\",\"link\":\"https:\\/\\/www.quantamagazine.org\\/insect-brains-melt-and-rewire-during-metamorphosis-20230726\\/\",\"title\":\"Why Insect Memories May Not Survive Metamorphosis\"},{\"type\":\"internal\",\"link\":\"https:\\/\\/www.quantamagazine.org\\/a-multitalented-scientist-seeks-the-origins-of-multicellularity-20240221\\/\",\"title\":\"A Multitalented Scientist Seeks the Origins of Multicellularity\"},{\"type\":\"internal\",\"link\":\"https:\\/\\/www.quantamagazine.org\\/single-cells-evolve-large-multicellular-forms-in-just-two-years-20210922\\/\",\"title\":\"Single Cells Evolve Large Multicellular Forms in Just Two Years\"}]}}\u003c\/script>\u003c/div>\n\u003cp>Genes involved in apoptosis may have come from former symbiotic partners that have since departed. Or they may be the results of horizontal gene transfer — a process once thought to be rare and now considered relatively widespread — where \u003ca href=\"https://www.quantamagazine.org/how-genes-can-leap-from-snakes-to-frogs-20221027/\">genes can hop\u003c/a> from one organism to another through processes that are \u003ca href=\"https://www.quantamagazine.org/dna-jumps-between-animal-species-no-one-knows-how-often-20210609\">still being worked out\u003c/a>. Packages of useful genes can leap between kingdoms of life and persist in new organisms if the benefits are great enough.\u003c/p>\n\u003cp>One of those benefits, strangely enough, seems to be programmed self-destruction.\u003c/p>\n\u003cp>All of this is important because it brings into focus the tangled reality underlying the glib phrase “survival of the fittest.” Evolution works in surprising ways, and genes have many purposes. Yet what is becoming clearer is that some sort of primitive collectivity — and, with it, organized self-sacrifices by living things — went on for possibly billions of years before multicellular life arose. Perhaps, as scientists continue to piece together the origins of cell death, we will find a broader notion of what death, and life, are for.\u003c/p>\n","fadein":false,"__typename":"ACFContent"},"$Post:136017.acf.series":{"name":null,"link":null,"__typename":"Term"},"$Post:136017.next.data.0":{"title":"Elliptic Curve &#8216;Murmurations&#8217; Found With AI Take Flight","link":"https://www.quantamagazine.org/elliptic-curve-murmurations-found-with-ai-take-flight-20240305/","categories":[{"type":"id","generated":true,"id":"$Post:136017.next.data.0.categories.0","typename":"Term"}],"featured_media_image":null,"acf":{"type":"id","generated":true,"id":"$Post:136017.next.data.0.acf","typename":"ACFFields"},"__typename":"Post"},"$Post:136017.next.data.0.categories.0":{"slug":"mathematics","__typename":"Term"},"$Post:136017.next.data.0.acf":{"template":"article","featured_block_title":"","featured_image_gif":false,"featured_image_default":{"type":"id","generated":true,"id":"$Post:136017.next.data.0.acf.featured_image_default","typename":"Image"},"featured_image_full_width":{"type":"id","generated":true,"id":"$Post:136017.next.data.0.acf.featured_image_full_width","typename":"Image"},"__typename":"ACFFields"},"$Post:136017.next.data.0.acf.featured_image_default":{"alt":"","caption":"","url":"https://d2r55xnwy6nx47.cloudfront.net/uploads/2024/03/Murmurations-byPaulChaikin-Default.webp","width":520,"height":292,"sizes":{"type":"id","generated":true,"id":"$Post:136017.next.data.0.acf.featured_image_default.sizes","typename":"ImageSizes"},"__typename":"Image"},"$Post:136017.next.data.